[1] Quick & slow wilts, black pepper - India (Kerala)
Date: Thu 2 Aug 2007
Source: Newindpress [edited]
<http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IER20070802012046&Page=R&Title=Kerala&Topic=0>

With a wide range of diseases affecting the cash crops it seems nature is
wreaking havoc on the farming community in the district [of Wayanad, Kerala
State]. Apart from devastating natural calamities, pests including wasps,
viruses, germs, fungus, and mites are causing untold suffering to farmers
there.
The 1st blows were dealt by quick-wilt and slow-wilt diseases that
completely destroyed the pepper cultivation, the backbone of the agrarian
economy in [the area]. In the Pulppalli-Mullankolli region, once known as
the pepper belt of the district, entire pepper vines disappeared leaving
only the supporting trees.
Then there was the fungus attack on arecanut. In thousands of hectares nuts
withered down. Farmers fought this by spraying a mixture of copper sulphate
and lime, but in vain.
Now, it is the turn of murikku trees [_Erythrina indica_ -- family
_Leguminoceae_, 'Indian coral'] used as the support tree for growing pepper
vines to fall victim to pest attack. Wasp attack on supporting trees had
disastrous results on pepper cultivation. According to experts the
_Quadrastichus erythrinae_ wasps [Erythrina gall wasp, a tropical plant
parasitic insect] eat away the murikku trees. "There is no doubt that we
can control the menace but as the wasp gets inside the tree, sucking the
sap, a high dosage of pesticide is needed to be sprayed on the tree. This
causes air pollution. Moreover, the toxic pesticides will also seep into
pepper vines causing health hazards," said V K Rajan, associate professor
of the Regional Agriculture Research Institute, Amabalavayal. "The disease
was reported about 10 months ago and we are in a dilemma," he added.
And losing faith in traditional crops farmers in large numbers recently
switched over to rubber cultivation, but that also got affected by various
diseases. Farmers despair that agriculture research institutions have
proved a failure in providing a solace to farmers. "The research
institutions of the state have proved to be a total failure in providing
any help to farmers," said M P Anirudhan, leader of a farmers' outfit at
Mullankolli. "Though our country is spending a huge sum of money for
maintaining such scientific establishments, the efficacy of such
institutions and their experts are questionable," he said.
--
